======================================================================
HOWL PHYS-24: TWO-LOOP UNIFICATION
======================================================================

THE RUNNING EQUATIONS (Level 1)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  One-loop:
    d(1/alpha_i)/d(ln mu) = -b_i / (2*pi)

  Two-loop:
    d(1/alpha_i)/d(ln mu) = -b_i / (2*pi)
                            - sum_j b_ij * alpha_j / (8*pi^2)

  The one-loop slopes are exact rationals (the b_i).
  The two-loop curvatures are exact rationals (the b_ij).
  Both are Level 1: determined by the gauge group and
  particle content, not by any measurement.

SM ONE-LOOP BETAS (Level 1, exact)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  b_1 = 41/10                              4.1
  b_2 = -19/6                              -3.1666666667
  b_3 = -7                                 -7.0

TWO-LOOP b_ij MATRIX (Level 1, exact)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  From Machacek-Vaughn (1983), Luo-Xiao (hep-ph/0207271).
  All entries are exact Fractions. Convention:
    d(1/a_i)/d(ln mu) includes -sum_j b_ij * a_j / (8*pi^2)

                 U(1)      SU(2)      SU(3)
           ---------- ---------- ----------
    U(1)       199/50      27/10       44/5
   SU(2)         9/10       35/6         12
   SU(3)        11/10        9/2        -26

  Decimal values:
                 U(1)      SU(2)      SU(3)
           ---------- ---------- ----------
    U(1)         3.98        2.7        8.8
   SU(2)          0.9     5.8333       12.0
   SU(3)          1.1        4.5      -26.0

THE DOMINANT TWO-LOOP EFFECT
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  The largest entry is b_33 = -26.
  This is the SU(3) self-coupling at two loops.

  At one loop, SU(3) runs as d(1/a3)/d(ln mu) = -b3/(2pi).
  At two loop, it gets a correction: -b_33 * a3 / (8*pi^2).

  Since b_33 = -26 (negative) and a3 > 0, the correction
  is POSITIVE: it SLOWS the SU(3) running.
  Slower SU(3) running means 1/a3 is LARGER at M_GUT,
  bringing it closer to the 1/a1 = 1/a2 crossing point.

  This is why two-loop improves unification: the dominant
  effect pulls alpha_3 toward the crossing, reducing Delta.

CABIBBO DOUBLET MODIFIED BETAS (Level 1, exact)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Db_1 = 1/15                              0.066666666667
  Db_2 = 1                                 1.0
  Db_3 = 1/3                               0.33333333333

  b_1' = 25/6                              4.1666666667
  b_2' = -13/6                             -2.1666666667
  b_3' = -20/3                             -6.6666666667

TWO-LOOP UNIFICATION RESULTS (Derived)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  From unification_test.py (6/6 checks), at M_VL = 500 GeV:

  One-loop Delta(1/alpha_3) (dimensionless) -1.17
  Two-loop Delta(1/alpha_3) (dimensionless) -0.4

  Improvement (%%)                         65.811965812

  The two-loop correction reduces the unification miss
  by two-thirds. The residual Delta = -0.4 is within the
  standard range for GUT threshold corrections in minimal
  SU(5) with ordinary mass splittings (factor 2-5 between
  heavy particles).

UNIFICATION QUALITY COMPARISON
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Scenario                          Gap Ratio        Delta    Quality
  ------------------------------ ------------ ------------ ----------
  SM (no BSM)                         1.89565        -6.58   Excluded
  SM + CD (one-loop)                  1.40741        -1.17       Poor
  SM + CD (two-loop)                  1.40741         -0.4       Near
  MSSM (one-loop)                         1.4        -0.69       Near

  The Cabibbo Doublet at two loops achieves the same
  unification quality as the MSSM at one loop: both need
  GUT threshold corrections of comparable magnitude.

WHAT REMAINS (Open)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  1. VL two-loop b_ij contribution (neglected, ~0.1%% effect)
  2. GUT threshold corrections: parametrize as function of
     M_T/M_X splitting in minimal SU(5) completion
  3. Find M_VL for exact unification (two-loop + thresholds)
  4. Predict alpha_s from unification condition
  5. Predict sin^2(theta_W) from 3/8 + running with CD betas

